      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "72c5d131e0b73bfd",
        "text": "Some of the things that make Agile work include teamwork and collaboration across functions and an uninterrupted flow of work that cut across functional silos enabling continuous delivery of value to the customers, fast feedback loops, and fast learning. In such a setting, the functional silos are replaced by business, or product/service, units. Everyone pulls their work to do from their product/service team's backlog, not the function's backlog. \n\nParadoxically forming an Agile Transformation Team or a team of Agile Coaches means adding one more functional silo, and team members pulling the work from the functional silo backlog and not the backlog of the teams they are supporting.\n\nInstead, change agents such as Transformation Leads and Agile Coaches should belong to and be embedded in the teams and departments they are supporting. They should be connected among themselves via a network and act in a federated way similar to the way Communities Of Practice work."
